Numerical variables exploration

Usually a ggpairs is pretty useful to start out an EDA.

ggpairs(df_train, columns = c(2,4,6,12,13,14), ggplot2::aes(colour=pay_response))

This is a little busy for me. Ill explore more in-depth below. ***However, lets keep this code since it produces all the correlation values super easily.

age <- ggplot(df_train, aes(x=age, fill=pay_response)) + geom_density(alpha=.6) + labs(title='Age Density - By Pay_Reponse')
fnlwgt <- ggplot(df_train, aes(x=age, y=fnlwgt, color=pay_response)) + geom_point() + labs(title='Age vs Fnlwgt') + facet_wrap(~pay_response)
edu_num <- ggplot(df_train, aes(x=age, y=capital_gain, color=pay_response)) + geom_point() + labs(title='Age vs Edu_num') + facet_wrap(~pay_response)
cap_gain <- ggplot(df_train, aes(x=age, y=capital_gain, color=pay_response)) + geom_point() + labs(title='Age vs Cap_Gain')
cap_loss <- ggplot(df_train, aes(x=age, y=capital_loss, color=pay_response)) + geom_point() + labs(title='Age vs Cap_Loss')
hours <- ggplot(df_train, aes(x=age, y=hours_per_week, color=pay_response)) + geom_point() + labs(title='Age vs Hours') + facet_wrap(~pay_response)

ggarrange(age, fnlwgt, edu_num, cap_gain, cap_loss, hours, nrow=2, ncol=3)

AGE DENSITY : Looks fine. The trend is especially apparent in the red curve.

AGE VS FNLWGT : I had to look this up, but Fnlwgt means final weight: This is the number of people that the census believes the point represents. Im not sure how this would fit into the pay_response model, so well have to evaluate its inclusion. As we can see, there are a bit of outliers. However, these outliers, if correct, count for +1M people, so.its weird.

AGE VS EDU NUM : While the relationship with pay_response appears pretty valid, some more exploration into capital_gain and education can help us understand what each num represents. I imagine education and capital_gain have a high amount of collinearity, so well have to evaluate which variable goes into the model.

AGE VS CAP GAIN : I dont really like this variable. I dont have a ton of understanding of what capital gain is, and the weird collection of outliers makes me think there is a limit to this variable.

AGE VS CAP_LOSS : This variable appears a little better to me. However, the trend is a little odd. I guess the takeaway is that the blue group has very few observations towards the bottom of the set.

AGE VS HOURS : I will have to visit this again and try to find a better way to visualize this.

HOURS DENSITY : Obviously, huge spike at 40. The colors make sense to melower hours_per_week would skew more red, and that is what we see.

On to categorical variables

count <- ggplot(df_train, aes(y=workclass, fill=workclass)) + geom_bar() + labs(title='Workclass Counts')
prop <- ggplot(df_train, aes(y=pay_response, fill=workclass)) + geom_bar(position='fill') + labs(title='Workclass Props by Pay_Response')

ggarrange(count, prop, nrow=1, ncol=2)

WORKCLASS COUNT : Here, we come across missing values ( ? ). Some research into census data may help us understand why it is there. But its most likely to large of a group (~2000) to remove outright.

WORKCLASS PROPS : Here, we can see that the classes (State-gov, Self-emp-inc, Self-emp-not-inc, Local-gov, Federal-gov) see an increase in representation in the >50K group. Private decreases its majority proportion when the pay_response increases.

count <- ggplot(df_train, aes(y=education, fill=education)) + geom_bar() + labs(title='education Counts')
prop <- ggplot(df_train, aes(y=pay_response, fill=education)) + geom_bar(position='fill') + labs(title='education Props by Pay_Response')

ggarrange(count, prop, nrow=1, ncol=2)

COUNTS : First thought, we should refactor these to order them from least to most experience. A lot of groups heremay be best to categorize into smaller groups (<high school, high-school, ba, ma, phd). Very cool that there is no ?.

PROPS: Minimizing the amount of groups will help with this chart. Although, we can see that college groups make up almost all of the >50K group.

count <- ggplot(df_train, aes(y=marital_status, fill=marital_status)) + geom_bar() + labs(title='marital_status Counts')
prop <- ggplot(df_train, aes(y=pay_response, fill=marital_status)) + geom_bar(position='fill') + labs(title='marital_status Props by Pay_Response')

ggarrange(count, prop, nrow=1, ncol=2)

COUNTS: Nothing significant here. No missing values though, so thats good. Again, consolidating some of these groups could maybe help create more significant groups within models.

PROPS: Big news here is that Never-married (and divorced, to a lesser extent) drops SIGNIFICANTLY between <50K and >50K. The Married-civ-spouse group sees the opposite change.

MY CONCLUSIONS:

Some of these variables have significant relationships with the reponse, some are a little harder to shoehorn into that relationship.

Maybe create Capital_Gain - Capital_Loss variable? Might help us understand the >50K population at high Cap_Loss values.

Consolidate groupsEducation/Country/Marital_Status, etc.

The ? values are concerning, especially considering that I cant think of a way to impute themwell have to talk about that.
